  id: 257,
  name: "Prompt Layer",
  description: "Prompt management and version control platform for teams building LLM applications and AI-powered products.",
  fullDescription: "Prompt Layer is a specialized development platform for engineering teams building applications on large language models (LLMs), providing centralized prompt management, version control, testing, and deployment infrastructure. As LLM applications move from prototypes to production, teams face challenges: prompts are scattered across codebases, changes break functionality unpredictably, testing is manual and inconsistent, and deployment lacks rollback capabilities. Prompt Layer addresses these with a Git-like workflow for prompt engineering. The platform stores all prompts in a centralized registry with version history, enabling teams to track changes, revert to previous versions, and understand who changed what and why. Each prompt version includes metadata: model used (GPT-4, Claude, Gemini), parameters (temperature, top_p, etc.), example inputs and expected outputs, and evaluation metrics. The testing framework automatically runs prompt changes against a test suite, flagging regressions before they reach production. Deployment features include canary rollouts (send 5% of traffic to new prompt version, monitor, then scale), A/B testing (compare performance of prompt variants in production), and instant rollback (revert to previous prompt version in seconds if issues detected). Prompt Layer integrates with major LLM providers, observability tools (LangSmith, Weights & Biases), and CI/CD pipelines (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI). The platform includes analytics dashboards showing prompt performance by version, cost per prompt, latency distributions, and drift detection (when model behavior changes over time). For teams moving from experimental LLM usage to production-grade systems, Prompt Layer provides the infrastructure discipline missing from the 'vibe coding' era of AI development. Enterprise features include SOC 2 compliance, audit logging, and role-based access controls. By treating prompts as code—with version control, testing, deployment, and monitoring—Prompt Layer enables teams to build reliable, iterable, and collaborative LLM applications at scale.",
