  id: 332,
  name: "drop.io",
  description: "Defunct file-sharing platform that enabled private document, picture, video, and audio sharing without accounts, acquired by Meta in 2010.",
  fullDescription: "Note: This tool is no longer active. drop.io was a file-sharing platform founded in 2007 and based in Brooklyn, New York, that offered a unique value proposition: users could store and share pictures, videos, audio, and documents privately without creating accounts, providing registration, or even needing an email address[citation:4]. The service raised a total of $3.9 million from investors including RRE Ventures, Gotham Ventures, and Rose Tech Ventures[citation:4]. In October 2010, drop.io was acquired by Meta (then Facebook) for $24 million[citation:4]. The simplicity of drop.io—creating temporary, password-protected 'drops' that could be used for file sharing without any personal information—was ahead of its time, anticipating the privacy concerns that would later become mainstream. After the acquisition, the service was gradually shut down, with many of its features and team members integrated into Meta's infrastructure. While the original drop.io is no longer available, its legacy influenced later privacy-focused file-sharing tools and temporary storage services. For users seeking similar functionality today, alternatives include services like Firefox Send (discontinued), WeTransfer, or privacy-focused options like OnionShare or Jumpshare. The story of drop.io serves as an example of how innovative startups can get acquired and absorbed by larger technology companies, with their features sometimes resurfacing years later in unexpected ways within the acquirer's product ecosystem.",
